Necessary Conditions for Reliable Propagation of Time-Varying Firing Rate¶

Authors: Navid Hasanzadeh, Mohammadreza Rezaei, Sayan Faraz, Milos R. Popovic, and Milad Lankarany

Abstract¶

Reliable propagation of slow-modulations of the firing rate across multiple layers of a feedforward network (FFN) has proven difficult to capture in spiking neural models. In this paper, we explore necessary conditions for reliable and stable propagation of time-varying asynchronous spikes whose instantaneous rate of changes in fairly short time windows [20 100] msec represents information of slow fluctuations of the stimulus. Specifically, we study the effect of network size, level of background synaptic noise, and the variability of synaptic delays in an FFN with all-to-all connectivity. We show that network size and the level of background synaptic noise, together with the strength of synapses, are substantial factors enabling the propagation of asynchronous spikes in deep layers of an FFN. In contrast, the variability of synaptic delays has a minor effect on signal propagation.

sns.set()


def default_style():
    """
        Setting the default style for figures. Settings here can change depending on if we want to generate figures for the
        notebook, paper, poster, etc.
    """
    sns.set(style="white")
    sns.set_context("talk", font_scale=1.0)
    plt.rc('axes',edgecolor='#FFFFFF')

def graph_psth(spikes, num_timesteps, save=None, color="#2598B2", title=None, xlabel=None, ylabel=None):
    """
        Graph peristimulus time histogram (PSTH) of given spike output over a period of time.
        
        Parameters:
        -----------
        spikes: numpy.ndarray
            Spikes from neuron. Dim 0: timestep, Dim 1: neuron index
        num_timesteps: int
            How many timesteps to graph for
        save: str, optional
            Filepath to save graph to, relative to notebook
        color: str, optional
        title: str, optional
        xlabel: str, optional
        ylabel: str, optional
        
        Returns:
        --------
        None
    """
    sns.set(style="white")
    sns.set_context("paper", font_scale=2.5)

    plt.rc('axes',edgecolor='#FFFFFF')

    in_spike_inds, in_spike_trial = np.where(spikes[:num_timesteps] > 0)
    in_spike_inds = in_spike_inds * 1.0e-4 #float(num_timesteps)

    plt.scatter(in_spike_inds*1000, in_spike_trial, s=6, marker='o', c=color)
    
    if title is not None:
        plt.title(title)
    if xlabel is not None:
        plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    if ylabel is not None:
        plt.ylabel(ylabel)


def graph_firing_rates(in_fr, out_fr, num_timesteps, save=None, in_color="#888888", out_color='#189B48'):
    """
        Graph Layer 1 vs Layer 2 firing rate over a period of time.
        
        Parameters:
        -----------
        in_fr: numpy.ndarray
            Firing rate of Layer 1 neurons. Dim 0: timestep, Dim 1: neuron index
        out_fr: numpy.ndarray
            Firing rate of Layer 1 neurons. Dim 0: timestep, Dim 1: neuron index
        num_timesteps: int
            How many timesteps to graph for
        save: str, optional
            Filepath to save graph to, relative to notebook
        in_color: str, optional
        out_color: str, optional
        
        Returns:
        --------
        None
    """
    sns.set(style="white")
#     sns.set_context("talk", font_scale=2.5)
    plt.rc('axes',edgecolor='#FFFFFF')

    t = np.arange(0, num_timesteps / 1.0e-4, 1e-4)

    plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))
    plt.ylim(top=60)

    plt.plot(t, in_fr.mean(1).numpy()[:num_timesteps], c=in_color, lw=5.0)
    plt.plot(t, out_fr.mean(1).numpy()[:num_timesteps], c=out_color, lw=5.0)

    sns.despine()
    
    if save is not None:
        plt.savefig(save, bbox_inches="tight")
    else:
        plt.show()
    plt.close()
    
    default_style()

network_sizes = [50, 100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 750, 1000]
noise_stds = [5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40]

LOAD_WEIGHTS = True
load_weights_mean_file = './weights/weights_mean.csv'
load_weights_stds_file = './weights/weights_std.csv'

if LOAD_WEIGHTS:
  weights_means = np.array(pd.read_csv(load_weights_mean_file))
  weights_stds = np.array(pd.read_csv(load_weights_stds_file))
  nn_size_noise = {}
  for i,nn_size in enumerate(network_sizes):
    nn_size_noise[nn_size] = {}
    for j,noise_std in enumerate(noise_stds):
      nn_size_noise[nn_size][noise_std] = [weights_means[i][j],weights_stds[i][j]]

WEIGHTS_DELAY = True
WEIGHTS_DELAY_MEAN = 0 #ms
WEIGHTS_DELAY_STD = 0
num_layers = 5
for NUM_NEURONS, BACKGROUND_NOISE in [(500,15), (500,30), (1000,40)]:
    test_i_inj = test_i_inj_copy
    print('--------------------------------------------------------------------')
    print('Network size={}, noise_std={} pA'.format(NUM_NEURONS,BACKGROUND_NOISE))
    CF_norm_test = np.zeros([len(network_sizes),len(noise_stds)])
    CC_test = np.zeros([len(network_sizes),len(noise_stds)])
    CF_FR_norm_test = np.zeros([len(network_sizes),len(noise_stds)])
    GPU_MODE = "cpu" # Change to "cpu" if you want to use CPU
    OUTs = [test_i_inj.flatten()]
    FRs = []
    fcl_out = None
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(30,12))
    sns.set_context("paper", font_scale=2.5)
    for l in range(num_layers):
        if l>0:
            test_i_inj = fcl_out.mean(1).numpy()[:10000].reshape(-1,1)
            OUTs.append(test_i_inj.flatten())
        ax = plt.subplot(2,int((num_layers+1)/2),l+1)
        plt.title('Layer {}'.format(l+1))
        sns.set_context("paper", font_scale=2.5)
        plt.rcParams["font.family"] = "Times New Roman"
        plt.rcParams['grid.alpha'] = 0.7
        fcl = FullyConnectedLayerTorched(NUM_NEURONS, std_noise=BACKGROUND_NOISE, device=GPU_MODE)
        fcl.train(i_inj=i_inj, exp_output=i_inj, dt=dt, t_stop=t_stop,num_iters=0)
        # Loading the pre-calculated Weights Distribution
        mu = nn_size_noise[NUM_NEURONS][BACKGROUND_NOISE][0]
        sigma = nn_size_noise[NUM_NEURONS][BACKGROUND_NOISE][1]
        weights_transfer = np.array([np.random.normal(mu, sigma, NUM_NEURONS) for i in range(0,NUM_NEURONS)])
        fcl.W = torch.tensor(weights_transfer)
        if l==0:
            fcl_out, fcl_V, fcl_F_binary, fcl_F_synaptic = fcl.output(test_i_inj, dt, test_t_stop,add_noise=True,random_delay=True,delay_mean=WEIGHTS_DELAY_MEAN,delay_std=WEIGHTS_DELAY_STD)
        else:
            fcl_out, fcl_V, fcl_F_binary, fcl_F_synaptic = fcl.output(test_i_inj, dt, test_t_stop,add_noise=True,random_delay=True,delay_mean=WEIGHTS_DELAY_MEAN,delay_std=WEIGHTS_DELAY_STD)
        fcl_out_2, a, fcl_spike_out, fcl_F_synaptic_2 = fcl.output(fcl_out, dt, test_t_stop,add_noise=True,random_delay=True,delay_mean=WEIGHTS_DELAY_MEAN,delay_std=WEIGHTS_DELAY_STD)
        fcl_in_fr,convolved_spikes = fcl.firing_rate(fcl_F_binary, dt, test_t_stop)
        graph_psth(fcl_F_binary,10000,save=None)
        if not(l==0 or l==3):
            ax.set_yticklabels([])
        if l<3:
            ax.set_xticklabels([])
        fcl_out_fr,convolved_spikes = fcl.firing_rate(fcl_spike_out, dt, test_t_stop)    
        if l==0:
            FRs.append(fcl_in_fr.mean(1).numpy()[:10000])
        FRs.append(fcl_out_fr.mean(1).numpy()[:10000])
        CF_FR = 1 -  np.linalg.norm(fcl_out_fr.mean(1).numpy() - fcl_in_fr.mean(1).numpy())/(np.linalg.norm(fcl_in_fr.mean(1).numpy())+0.0001*np.random.rand())
        CF_FR_norm_test[i][j] = CF_FR

    sns.set_context("paper", font_scale=2.5)
    ax = plt.subplot(2,int((num_layers+1)/2),6)
    plt.grid()
    for ii, fr in enumerate(FRs[:-1]):
        plt.plot(test_t[:10000]*1000,fr,label='Layer {}'.format(ii+1),linewidth=5)
    plt.legend(loc=(1.04,0),edgecolor="white",prop={'size': 22})
    plt.ylabel("Inst. Firing Rate (spikes/s)",labelpad=15,fontsize='large')
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, frameon=False)
    plt.tick_params(labelcolor='none', top='off', bottom='off', left='off', right='off')
    ax.set_xlabel("Time" + " (msec)",labelpad=15,fontsize='x-large',fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_ylabel('Network size={}, noise std={} pA, delay std={} ms'.format(NUM_NEURONS,BACKGROUND_NOISE,WEIGHTS_DELAY_STD),fontsize='large',labelpad=18,fontweight='bold')
    plt.show()
